This paper deals with algorithmic problems related to integer multiplication and convolution, which are fundamental problems in computer science. The paper presents tight bounds for these problems in the cell-probe model with word size w, which is a common model of computation in theoretical computer science. The paper also mentions that these problems have a wide range of practical applications, which suggests that they are relevant to many subfields of computer science. Based on these factors, it is likely that this paper would be classified under several sub-categories, including cs.DS (data structures and algorithms), cs.CC (computational complexity), cs.IT (information theory), cs.DM (discrete mathematics), and cs.NA (numerical analysis).
